

Now we will check & suggest the package name when creating a new Gradle project.

- In simple mode, the package name will be automatically normalized.
- In advanced mode, during specific package name step, the default name will be normalized:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/45906942/162724057-8a0c63bd-6bbb-4e77-8bf6-276e7d2e3cfb.png)
the default package name is normalized from `cs-proj`(the folder name) to `cs.proj`
- when you try to use an invalid name, the inputbox will be disabled and show error message and suggestion.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/45906942/162724359-01731794-c183-49d9-a978-df0c0ffab95d.png)

Run "Developer: Reload with Extensions Disabled" from command palette, and manually enable "Language Support for Java" extension only, see if the problem is gone. - Second, to find out the culprit. 'body': "In both the signature help and in the completion resolve path ad-hoc
cached ThreadPool instances were created and not shutdown properly.

Using the same ExecutorService instance can avoid spawning new threads,
which is cheaper than re-creating new threads all time. A quick
benchmark:

		ExecutorsBenchmark.createAdhocThreadPool          avgt   10  124.947 ± 1.527  us/op
		ExecutorsBenchmark.reuseThreadPool                avgt   10   14.979 ± 1.234  us/op

But more importantly the instances weren't shutdown after use, leaking
resources.

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/mfussenegger/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "In both the signature help and in the completion resolve path ad-hoc
cached ThreadPool instances were created and not shutdown properly.

Using the same ExecutorService instance can avoid spawning new threads,
which is cheaper than re-creating new threads all time. A quick
benchmark:

		ExecutorsBenchmark.createAdhocThreadPool          avgt   10  124.947 ± 1.527  us/op
		ExecutorsBenchmark.reuseThreadPool                avgt   10   14.979 ± 1.234  us/op

But more importantly the instances weren't shutdown after use, leaking
resources.

'body': "In both the signature help and in the completion resolve path ad-hoc
cached ThreadPool instances were created and not shutdown properly.

Using the same ExecutorService instance can avoid spawning new threads,
which is cheaper than re-creating new threads all time. A quick
benchmark:

		ExecutorsBenchmark.createAdhocThreadPool          avgt   10  124.947 ± 1.527  us/op
		ExecutorsBenchmark.reuseThreadPool                avgt   10   14.979 ± 1.234  us/op

But more importantly the instances weren't shutdown after use, leaking
resources.

Basic use cases:
- On startup. When user launchs an app, live connection is connected, sts-vscode sends notificaiton via `onDidLiveProcessConnect`, dashboad queries beans/mappings data via `getLiveProcessData` (currently it's from cache, but should be consistent), and visualizes the data in tree view.
- On stop. When user stops an app (or disconnect the live connection), sts-vsocde sends notification via `onDidLiveProcessDisconnect`, dashboard then reset the tree view to default.

Advanced use cases (if valid and feasible to implement):
- On refresh/change/hot reload. AFAIK currently live data is only updated via a manual `refresh`. There's possiblity that live data in cache is dirty. 
  - An ideal way is the "push" model. Whenever sts-vscode knows that cached data is updated, it sends a notification e.g. `onDidLiveDataUpdated`, then downstream extensions like dashboard can re-fetch the data. If that's not easy to implement, at least whenever a manual 'refresh' finishes, sts-vscode should send the notification, and dashboard can update the corresponding view.
  - A fallback solution is "pull", not preferred. We change the `get` function a little bit, allowing a `forceToRefresh` param. Then dashboard can poll sts-vscode with some interval, and always update the UI with latest data. I assume that would bring a lot of  overhead.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/spring-projects/sts4/issues/comments/1088192627/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

I have and extrange behavior in VSCode with "Maven for Java" extension:

- If I compile my maven project from Windows 10 cmd terminal or VSCode embedded terminal ("mvn clean" and "mvn package"), maven **works fine**
- If I compile my maven project from VSCode with "right click" over Maven Extension over my project, and then "left click" over "clean" and "left click" over "package" it **works fine** 
- However, all the time my IDE shows a red alert over my project pom.xml. If I open the pom.xml, I can see a red underline over <parent> tag showing the following message:

> Project build error: Non-resolvable parent POM for my.package:my-proyect:0.0.1-SNAPSHOT: org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-parent:pom:2.3.8.RELEASE failed to transfer from https://repo.maven.apache.org/maven2 during a previous attempt. As a subsidiary problem, my project doesn't show up in "Spring Boot Dashboard"

Ok, we have a proxy at the organization so, up to now, behavior seems common. **The point is**: in my organization, we work with a local maven repository. We don't use repo.maven.apache.org but a local URI. In fact, when I run "mvn clean; mvn package" from Windows 10 cmd I can see messages like "Downloading dependency from 10.0.0.200" so my settings.xml file should be working properly.

However, for some reason, "Maven for Java" plugin seems to be trying to resolve dependencys from "https://repo.maven.apache.org/maven2".

My developping enviroment is:
 - Windows 10
 - I have my local copy of maven executable (v3.8.5) at the following path: C:\ENTORNO2022.00\01.SOFTWARE\03.HERRAMIENTAS\apache-maven-3.8.5
 - Settings.xml file is at C:\ENTORNO2022.00\01.SOFTWARE\03.HERRAMIENTAS\apache-maven-3.8.5\conf\settings.xml
 - VisualStudioCode version 1.65.2
 - Maven for Java v0.35.1

Settings.json from my VSCode is 

> {
>     "java.configuration.maven.globalSettings": "C:\\ENTORNO2022.00\\01.SOFTWARE\\03.HERRAMIENTAS\\apache-maven-3.8.5\\conf\\settings.xml",
>     "java.configuration.maven.userSettings": "C:\\ENTORNO2022.00\\01.SOFTWARE\\03.HERRAMIENTAS\\apache-maven-3.8.5\\conf\\settings.xml",
>     "maven.settingsFile": "C:\\ENTORNO2022.00\\01.SOFTWARE\\03.HERRAMIENTAS\\apache-maven-3.8.5\\conf\\settings.xml",
>     "maven.executable.path": "mvn",
>     "maven.executable.preferMavenWrapper": false,
>     "maven.terminal.useJavaHome": true,
>     "workbench.startupEditor": "none",
>     "redhat.telemetry.enabled": true,
> }


Could any one provide some help. I don't know what to. Thank you very much

I have and extrange behavior in VSCode with "Maven for Java" extension:

- If I compile my maven project from Windows 10 cmd terminal or VSCode embedded terminal ("mvn clean" and "mvn package"), maven **works fine**
- If I compile my maven project from VSCode with "right click" over Maven Extension over my project, and then "left click" over "clean" and "left click" over "package" it **works fine** 
- However, all the time my IDE shows a red alert over my project pom.xml. If I open the pom.xml, I can see a red underline over <parent> tag showing the following message:

> Project build error: Non-resolvable parent POM for my.package:my-proyect:0.0.1-SNAPSHOT: org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-parent:pom:2.3.8.RELEASE failed to transfer from https://repo.maven.apache.org/maven2 during a previous attempt. As a subsidiary problem, my project doesn't show up in "Spring Boot Dashboard"

Ok, we have a proxy at the organization so, up to now, behavior seems common. **The point is**: in my organization, we work with a local maven repository. We don't use repo.maven.apache.org but a local URI. In fact, when I run "mvn clean; mvn package" from Windows 10 cmd I can see messages like "Downloading dependency from 10.0.0.200" so my settings.xml file should be working properly.

However, for some reason, "Maven for Java" plugin seems to be trying to resolve dependencys from "https://repo.maven.apache.org/maven2".

My developping enviroment is:
 - Windows 10
 - I have my local copy of maven executable (v3.8.5) at the following path: C:\ENTORNO2022.00\01.SOFTWARE\03.HERRAMIENTAS\apache-maven-3.8.5
 - Settings.xml file is at C:\ENTORNO2022.00\01.SOFTWARE\03.HERRAMIENTAS\apache-maven-3.8.5\conf\settings.xml
 - VisualStudioCode version 1.65.2
 - Maven for Java v0.35.1

Settings.json from my VSCode is 

> {
>     "java.configuration.maven.globalSettings": "C:\\ENTORNO2022.00\\01.SOFTWARE\\03.HERRAMIENTAS\\apache-maven-3.8.5\\conf\\settings.xml",
>     "java.configuration.maven.userSettings": "C:\\ENTORNO2022.00\\01.SOFTWARE\\03.HERRAMIENTAS\\apache-maven-3.8.5\\conf\\settings.xml",
>     "maven.settingsFile": "C:\\ENTORNO2022.00\\01.SOFTWARE\\03.HERRAMIENTAS\\apache-maven-3.8.5\\conf\\settings.xml",
>     "maven.executable.path": "mvn",
>     "maven.executable.preferMavenWrapper": false,
>     "maven.terminal.useJavaHome": true,
>     "workbench.startupEditor": "none",
>     "redhat.telemetry.enabled": true,
> }


Could any one provide some help. I don't know what to. Thank you very much

That's provided by [Java Extension](https://github.com/redhat-developer/vscode-java), which is imports and compile your project via m2e. Looks like it ignores the proxy for some reason.  **I suggest that you create an issue there, providing [correponding log](https://github.com/redhat-developer/vscode-java/wiki/Troubleshooting#enable-logging) if there's any.** 

These settings look good to me. BTW, Java extension reads those settings starting with "java" and this Maven extension reads those staring with "maven".

> As a subsidiary problem, my project doesn't show up in "Spring Boot Dashboard"

That's because "Spring Boot Dashboard" depends on "Java Extension" to get proper project information.

'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Defining a custom `context-path` like e.g. `server.servlet.context-path=/example` (in `application.properties`) is not being handled by the 'Open in Webbrowser' functionality.

One option would be to enhance the current [JMXService-Helper](https://github.com/microsoft/vscode-spring-boot-dashboard/blob/main/java-extension/src/main/java/com/microsoft/vscode/spring/boot/dashboard/java/extension/JmxService.java) to also lookup the aforementioned property and construct the path with it by modifying [Controller.ts](https://github.com/microsoft/vscode-spring-boot-dashboard/blob/main/src/Controller.ts) in line 149.

Another option would be to have a custom property that could be set per Workplace to force an URL path.
E.g. something like `spring.dashboard.urlPath` in `{workplace}/.vscode/settings.json` that supports placeholders so that something like setting 
```json
{
"spring.dashboard.urlPath": "https://localhost:${port}/example"
}
```
would be possible. This would be even better for scenarios where starting at a different URL is desired.

If this would be implemented one would be able to create a Spring Boot app with a custom context-path and have the 'Open in Webbrowser' functionality automatically open at the correct path without always needing to type the context path in the Browser URL bar after being greeted with the 404 screen.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/microsoft/vscode-spring-boot-dashboard/issues/161/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/microsoft/vscode-spring-boot-dashboard/issues/161/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

`server.servlet.context-path` from the Spring Boot properties.

remote code development with VScode and java plugin, however the java plugin is not detecting the java installation on the remote node and therefore the language server cannot start.

the issue is similar to  #1092 which even mention that the problem also happens when installation  of sdk is done with asdf, however the issue was closed but the asdf installation is still broken.

JAVA_HOME is correctly exported by asdf for both bash and zsh.


##### Environment
- Operating System: OSX with remote containers to debian buster
- JDK version: tried with both Zulu and AdoptOpenjdk version 11.
- Visual Studio Code version: 1.58.1
- Java extension version: 0.80.0

##### Steps To Reproduce
1. remote linux installation debian buster without systems jdk. installed via asdf
2. connect to the remote node with vscode and try to open a project with java files.

[Please attach a sample project reproducing the error]
https://github.com/danielporto/gRPC-Java-snippet/

##### Current Result
vscode stuck in java plugin welcome page and never detects the jdk installation on the remote node.

##### Expected Result
vscode detect java installation.
